s many institutions in American society—including the labor market, the welfare state, the criminal justice system, and schools and universities. Looking beyond the stalled debate over current antidiscrimination policies, the authors also put forth a fresh vision for achieving genuine racial equality of opportunity in a post-affirmative action world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aRacismxUnited States. 0aRacismzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Race & Ethnic Relations.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aafrican americans.  aamerica.  aamerican culture.  aamerican society.  abigotry.  ablack americans.  acolor blindness.  acriminal justice system.  acriminologists.  acultural criticism.  aeconomists.  ahealth care discrimination.  ahistorians.  ahousing discrimination.  alegal scholars.  alow income families.  aneo conservatives.  apolitical scientists.  aracial discrimination.  aracial inequality.  aracial issues.  aracial prejudice.  asociologists.  aunited states.  awage gaps.  awelfare state.  awhite americans.  awhitewashing.1 aCarnoy, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aCurrie, Elliott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aOppenheimer, David B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093875540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520938755423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520938755/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles